Subject: bits: bit_write_DD aliased the pointer, not the value, and compared
 the wrong bytes

bit_write_DD selected the DD compression mode from
`(const uint16_t *)&uchar_value` — the address of the local pointer
variable, not the double's bytes — so the 4/6-byte partial-mode writes
were chosen from stack-address garbage and corrupted the value
(nondeterministically; it mostly fell into full-double mode, which is why
it usually worked). It also compared the LOW 16-bit words, but bit_read_DD
keeps the HIGH bytes of the default (word3 for code 2, words 2+3 for code
1). Alias the value bytes and compare the high words so the encoder mode
matches the reader. bits_test extended; all 254 unit tests pass.

Co-authored-by: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>

--- a/src/bits.c
+++ b/src/bits.c
@@ -1281,8 +1281,13 @@ bit_write_DD (Bit_Chain *dat, double value, double default_value)
       const unsigned char *uchar_value = (const unsigned char *)&value;
       const unsigned char *uchar_default
           = (const unsigned char *)&default_value;
-      const uint16_t *uint_value = (const uint16_t *)&uchar_value;
-      const uint16_t *uint_default = (const uint16_t *)&uchar_default;
-      // dbl: 7654 3210, little-endian only
-      // check the first 2 bits for eq
-      if (le16toh (uint_value[0]) == le16toh (uint_default[0]))
+      // Alias the DOUBLE bytes, not the address of the pointer variable.
+      const uint16_t *uint_value = (const uint16_t *)uchar_value;
+      const uint16_t *uint_default = (const uint16_t *)uchar_default;
+      // dbl: 7654 3210, little-endian only. bit_read_DD keeps the HIGH bytes
+      // of the default, so pick the mode by the high words, not the low.
+      if (le16toh (uint_value[3]) == le16toh (uint_default[3]))
         {
-          if (le16toh (uint_value[1]) == le16toh (uint_default[1]))
+          if (le16toh (uint_value[2]) == le16toh (uint_default[2]))
